// Fires when sessions-hub logs a hub.certs.cf_auth_failed event within the last
// hour — i.e. the Cloudflare API returned 401/403 to a cert sign, revoke, or
// status(poll) call. That is NOT ordinary CF flakiness: it means the
// CF_CLIENT_CERT_TOKEN the hub uses to mint/revoke mTLS client certs is expired,
// revoked, or under-scoped, so EVERY rotation operation will keep failing until
// the token is rotated. Left unnoticed this is silent: renewals 502, the daily
// prune can't revoke displaced certs, and stale certs stay valid at the CA. This
// alert turns a dead token into an email instead of a slow-burning outage.
//
// Configure the scheduled-query rule to fire on count >= 1 over the window (a
// single occurrence is already actionable — one dead token fails everything).
// Remediation: mint a replacement API token (see below) and update the
// CF_CLIENT_CERT_TOKEN secret (`wrangler secret put CF_CLIENT_CERT_TOKEN`).
//
// The token this alert guards should be minted:
//   - expiry ~1 year out (expires_on), and its rotation tracked BEFORE it lapses
//     — an expired token is exactly what trips this alert;
//   - zone-scoped to the sessions zone (not account-wide);
//   - with the single permission SSL and Certificates:Edit (mint + revoke client
//     certs), nothing broader.
//
// hub.certs.cf_auth_failed is emitted by reportCfAuthFailure() in
// hub/src/api/certs.ts, wired into all three CF API call sites (sign / revoke /
// status), carrying { op, cert_id, http_status }. It is deliberately separate
// from the generic hub.certs.sign_failed / *_error logs so a token problem is
// distinguishable from a per-cert rejection or a transient network error.
//
// See missed-heartbeat.kql for the OTelLogs/Body-as-JSON assumption this query
// shares. ASSUMPTION TO VERIFY AT M4 DEPLOY: confirm the table/column names once
// real data flows.

// `otel` wraps OTelLogs in `union isfuzzy=true` so a missing table (before the
// first OTLP log lands) degrades to empty instead of erroring the whole rule —
// see missed-heartbeat.kql's "Missing-table guard" note for the full rationale.
let otel = union isfuzzy=true
    (datatable(TimeGenerated:datetime, Body:string)[]),
    (OTelLogs | project TimeGenerated, Body);
otel
| where TimeGenerated > ago(1h)
| extend body = todynamic(Body)
| where body.event == "hub.certs.cf_auth_failed"
| extend op = tostring(body.op), cert_id = tostring(body.cert_id), http_status = toint(body.http_status)
| project TimeGenerated, op, cert_id, http_status
